data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","sequence_number":215,"item_id":"msg_0cf6a058db161ce70069265b380da0819497311680708b8d58","output_index":2,"content_index":0,"text":"According to Wikipedia, Euler's Identity, expressed as \\( e^{i\\pi} + 1 = 0 \\), is one of the most famous and beautiful equations in mathematics. It connects five of the most fundamental mathematical constants: \\( e \\), the base of natural logarithms; \\( i \\), the imaginary unit where \\( i^2 = -1 \\); \\( \\pi \\), the ratio of the circumference to the diameter of a circle; 1, the multiplicative identity; and 0, the additive identity. This simple yet profound relationship arises as a special case of Euler's formula, \\( e^{ix} = \\cos(x) + i\\sin(x) \\), evaluated at \\( x = \\pi \\). \n\nEuler's Identity is celebrated for its mathematical elegance and its connection to different parts of mathematics, including exponential functions and trigonometry. It has been described as exemplifying \"mathematical beauty\" because it integrates fundamental numerical constants and basic arithmetic operations in one concise equation.","logprobs":[]}

